A butyl group is a relatively large hydrophobic alkyl chain, which usually tends to decrease the melting point because it disrupts the crystal lattice of the solid, but due to its length in this case, it likely adds some van der Waals interactions, slightly increasing the melting point. name: 4-butylphenol
source: Dreisbach R. R. Physical Properties of Chemical Compounds; Vol. I; American Chemical Society; Washington; 1955.
Reason: Starting with the basic unit, benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. Adding a hydroxyl group (OH) introduces hydrogen bonding, which generally raises the melting point significantly. However, the increase is not typically as much as +100°C; a more realistic increase might be around +40°C for strong intermolecular hydrogen bonding. A butyl group is a hydrophobic alkyl chain, which usually tends to depress the melting point due to a disruption in the crystal lattice of the solid as it hinders close packing of the molecules. But since it also adds some van der Waals interactions due to increased molecular size and surface area, it can lead to a moderate increase in the melting point. This increase is typically around +5°C for each carbon in the alkyl chain. With four carbons, this would suggest an increase of about +20°C. The net effect of the butyl group could potentially offset some of the increases due to the hydroxyl group. However, given the actual value, it appears the depressant effect of the butyl group is stronger than the increment due to van der Waals interactions in this case.
